Production
=Development=
quote box|align=right|width=35%|quote="That's really the essence of the story, it's a very unusual love story in a very strange environment, a very strange sort of landscape, and that is I think the abiding theme of the film. It is how these two characters, these two real people transcend all the complications and curveballs that life throws at them."|source=—James Marsh (director)|James Marsh, speaking of the film's nature<ref name=Deadline.com-Oscar>cite web|title=First look at Oscar contender 'The Theory of Everything' — an unexpected love story about Stephen Hawking|url=http://Deadline.com/2014/08/theory-of-everything-trailer-stephen-hawking-eddie-redmayne-first-look-video-814507/|date=6 August 2014|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=6 August 2014</ref>
Screenwriter Anthony McCarten had been interested in Hawking since reading his seminal book ''A Brief History of Time'' in 1988. In 2004, McCarten read Jane Hawking's memoir ''Travelling to Infinity: My Life with Stephen'', and subsequently began writing a screenplay adaptation of the book, with no guarantees in place. He met numerous times with Jane at her home to discuss the project.  After multiple drafts, he was introduced in 2009 to producer Lisa Bruce via their mutual ICM agent, Craig Bernstein.<ref>cite web|last=Levy|first=Emmanuel|title=Theory of Everything: making movie about Stephen Hawkings|url=http://EmanuelLevy.com/pick-of-the-week/theory-of-everything-making-the-movie-about-stephen-hawkings|date=5 September 2014|website=EmanuelLevy.com|publisher=Emmanuel Levy|accessdate=16 September 2014</ref>

Bruce spent three years with McCarten, further convincing Jane Hawking to agree to a film adaptation of her book, with Bruce stating, "It was a lot of conversation, many glasses of sherry, and many pots of tea".<ref>cite news|title=Toronto: THR Honors 'Theory of Everything' stars and director with breakthrough in film awards|url=http://www.HollywoodReporter.com/news/toronto-thr-honors-theory-everything-730776|date=7 September 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=7 September 2014</ref> On 18 April 2013, James Marsh (director)|James Marsh was confirmed to direct the film, with the shooting being based in Cambridge, and at other locations in the United Kingdom,citation needed|date=May 2015|reason=Guardian article cited at end of sentence does not confirm Marsh as director. It simply says ''looks set to take charge''. Also, no explicit mention is made of any shooting locations. with Eddie Redmayne courted to fill the male lead of the piece.<ref>cite web |last=Child |first=Ben |title=Eddie Redmayne set to play Stephen Hawking in biopic|url=https://www.TheGuardian.com/film/2013/jun/13/eddie-redmayne-stephen-hawking-theory-of-everything |accessdate=11 April 2014|website=TheGuardian.com|publisher=The Guardian|date=18 April 2013</ref> On 23 June 2013, it was revealed that Felicity Jones was confirmed to play the film's female lead role opposite Redmayne.<ref>cite news|last=White|first=James|title=Felicity Jones joins Theory of Everything |url=http://www.EmpireOnline.com/news/story.asp?NID=37894|date=23 June 2013|website=EmpireOnline.com|publisher=Empire Magazine|accessdate=23 June 2013</ref><ref>cite news|last=Armitage|first=Hugh|title=Felicity Jones cast in Stephen Hawking biopic 'Theory of Everything' |url=http://www.DigitalSpy.co.uk/movies/news/a492578/felicity-jones-cast-in-stephen-hawking-biopic-theory-of-everything.html#~oNtbX5UTI1Rxmd |date=24 June 2013 |website=DigitalSpy.co.uk |publisher=Digital Spy|accessdate=24 June 2013</ref>  On 8 October 2013, it was confirmed that Emily Watson and David Thewlis had joined the cast, Christina Applegate, Kate del Castillo, Catherine Tate, and Amanda Peet were considered for the part,<ref>cite news |last=Bullock |first=Dan|title=Emily Watson joins Working Title's 'Theory of Everything'|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/emily-watson-joins-working-titles-theory-of-everything-1200705092/|date=8 October 2013|website=Variety.com|publisher=Variety (magazine)|Variety|accessdate=8 October 2013</ref> and that Working Title's Tim Bevan, Eric Fellner, Lisa Bruce, and Anthony McCarten would be producing the piece.<ref name=HollywoodReporterChild>cite news |last=Child|first=Ben|title=Eddie Redmayne, Felicity Jones line up for James Marsh's 'The Theory of Everything' |url=http://www.HollywoodReporter.com/news/eddie-redmayne-felicity-jones-line-644957 |date=8 October 2013 |work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=8 October 2013</ref>

Marsh had studied archival images to give the film its authenticity, stating, "When we had photographs and documentary footage of Stephen that related to our story, we tried to reproduce them as best we could".<ref name=InsideMovies>cite web|title=Eddie Redmayne on playing (and meeting) Stephen Hawking|url=http://InsideMovies.ew.com/2014/08/18/the-theory-of-everything-eddie-redmayne-talks-playing-and-meeting-stephen-hawking/|date=18 August 2014 |website=InsideMovies.ew.com|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=18 August 2014</ref> Redmayne met with Stephen Hawking|Hawking himself, commenting, "Even now, when he's unable to move, you can still see such effervescence in his eyes". And described portraying Hawking on-screen as a "hefty" challenge, adding that, "The real problem with making a film is of course you don't shoot chronologically. So it was about having to really try and chart his physical deterioration [so] you can jump into it day-to-day, whilst at the same time keeping this spark and wit and humour that he has".<ref name=InsideMovies/>

Redmayne spent six months researching Hawking's life, watching every piece of interview footage he could find of him.<ref name=VarietyCry>cite news |title=Toronto: 'The Theory of Everything' made Stephen Hawking cry|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/toronto-the-theory-of-everything-made-stephen-hawking-cry-1201300436/|date=7 September 2014|website=Variety.com|publisher=Variety (magazine)|Variety|accessdate=7 September 2014</ref> He studied Hawking's accent and speech patterns under dialect coach Julia Wilson-Dickson to prepare for the role.<ref name=guardian>cite web |first=Andrew |last=Wilson-Dickson |title=Julia Wilson-Dickson obituary|url=https://www.TheGuardian.com/film/2015/oct/18/julia-wilson-dickson-obituary |website=TheGuardian.com|publisher=The Guardian|date=18 October 2015|accessdate=14 November 2015</ref> Marsh stated that what Redmayne had to do was not easy. "He had to take on enormous amounts of difficult preparation, as well as embracing the difficult physicality of the role. It's not just doing a disability. It's actually charting the course of an illness that erodes the body, and the mind has to project out from that erosion", he said. He added that Hawking gave him his blessing, and also revealed that, "[Hawking's] response was very positive, so much so that he offered to lend his voice, the real voice that he uses. The voice you hear in the latter part of the story is in fact Stephen's actual electronic voice as he uses it", he said.<ref name=Deadline.com-Oscar/> It was revealed to the Toronto International Film Festival (TIFF) audience that as the lights came up at a recent screening, a nurse had wiped a tear from Hawking's cheek.<ref name=VarietyCry/>

Jane Hawking, speaking on BBC Radio 4's ''Woman's Hour'', talked of meeting Jones several times while the latter prepared for the role.<ref name="Woman's Hour 2 January 2015">cite episode| title= Jane Hawking; Surrogacy; Same Clothes Every Day; Safe Houses for Over-45s| episodelink= | series= Woman's Hour| credits= Presenter: Sheila McClennon; Producer: Susannah Tresilian; Interviewed Guest: Jane Hawking| network= BBC| station= BBC Radio 4 |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b04vqvbs | airdate= 2 January 2015| minutes= 03:30| accessdate= 7 October 2017 </ref> When Hawking saw the finished film, she was amazed to see that Jones had incorporated her mannerisms and speech patterns into her performance.<ref name="Woman's Hour 2 January 2015"/>

=Filming=
File:Bridge over the River Cam, Cambridge, 2008-03-31.jpg|thumb|Part of the filming in Cambridge took place at St John's College, Cambridge|St John's College
By 8 October 2013, principal photography had begun, with the shooting being done at Cambridge University, and at other locations in Cambridgeshire and across the United Kingdom.<ref>cite web|last=Bullock|first=Dan|title=Hawking biopic 'The Theory of Everything' starring Eddie Redmayne begins filming|url=http://www.TheHollywoodNews.com/2013/10/09/hawking-biopic-theory-everything-starring-eddie-redmayne-begins-filming/|date=9 October 2013 |website=TheHollywoodNews.com|publisher=The Hollywood News|accessdate=9 October 2013</ref>  
Prior to the start of principal photography, Working Title had begun shooting on the lawn in front of the St John's College, Cambridge#New Court's Clock Tower|New Court building from 23 September 2013 to 27 September 2013; they filmed the Cambridge May Ball scene, set in 1963 in the United Kingdom|1963.<ref>cite web|title=Felicity about Theory of Everything – shooting of the May Ball & Boat Club scenes |url=http://AddictedToEddie.blogspot.co.uk/2014/03/felicity-jones-about-theory-of.html |date=26 March 2014 |website=AddictedToEddie.blogspot.co.uk |publisher=Addicted to Eddie's blog |accessdate=26 March 2014</ref>  On 24 September 2013, scenes were filmed at St John's College, Cambridge|St John's College, The Backs in Queen's Road, Cambridge|Queen's Road, and Queen's Green.<ref>cite news|last=Armitage|first=Hugh|title=Exclusive: first pictures of Eddie Redmayne playing Stephen Hawking on film shoot in Cambridge for The Theory of Everything|url=http://www.Cambridge-News.co.uk/Cambridge/EXCLUSIVE-First-pictures-of-Eddie-Redmayne-playing-Stephen-Hawking-on-film-shoot-in-Cambridge-for-The-Theory-of-Everything-movie-20130924155445.htm|date=24 September 2013|website=Cambridge-News.co.uk|publisher=Cambridge News|accessdate=24 September 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131009203249/http://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/Cambridge/EXCLUSIVE-First-pictures-of-Eddie-Redmayne-playing-Stephen-Hawking-on-film-shoot-in-Cambridge-for-The-Theory-of-Everything-movie-20130924155445.htm|archivedate=9 October 2013|df=dmy-all</ref>  The New Court lawn and List of bridges in Cambridge#Kitchen Bridge, St John's College (1709–11)|Kitchen Bridge were included features in the filming location of the piece.  The May Ball scene was the last of the outside shoots, with filming in a lecture theatre the following day, and the remaining filming completed in the studio over the final five weeks of production.<ref name=Scudamores>cite web|title=Cambridge Theory of Everything|url=http://www.Scudamores.com/theory-of-everything|date=1 October 2013|website=Scudamores.com|publisher=Scudamores|accessdate=1 October 2013</ref>

The pyrotechnic specialists Titanium Fireworks, who developed the displays for the London 2012 Olympic Games, provided three identical firework displays for the Trinity College, Cambridge May Ball scene.<ref name=Scudamores/><ref>cite web|title=Trinity College Cambridge May Ball fireworks 2014 |url=http://www.TitaniumFireworks.com/trinity-college-cambridge-may-ball-2014/ |date=20 June 2014|website=TitaniumFireworks.com|publisher=Titanium Fireworks |accessdate=20 June 2014</ref>

=Music=
Composer Jóhann Jóhannsson scored ''The Theory of Everything''.  His score in the film has been described as including "[Jóhannsson's] signature blend of acoustic instruments and electronics". Jóhannsson commented that "it always involves the layers of live recordings, whether it's orchestra or a band or solo instrument, with electronics and more 'soundscapey' elements which can come from various sources".<ref>cite web|title=General news scores soundtrack: Jóhann Jóhannsson provides the beautiful score for Focus Features' The Theory of Everything|url=http://www.WeAreMovieGeeks.com/2014/08/johann-johannsson-provides-the-beautiful-score-for-focus-features-the-theory-of-everything/|date=26 August 2014|website=WeAreMovieGeeks.com|publisher=We Are Movie Geeks|accessdate=26 August 2014</ref> Jóhannsson's score was highly praised, being nominated for an Academy Award for Best Original Score, a BAFTA Award for Best Film Music, a Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Score and a Grammy Award for Best Score Soundtrack for Visual Media, winning the Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score. The soundtrack was recorded at Abbey Road Studios.<ref>cite web|title=Recording at Abbey Road for Jóhann Jóhannsson 'Theory of Everything' feature film music|url=http://www.Bakermoon.com/2014/08/recording-in-abbey-road-for-johann-johannsson-theory-of-everything-feature-film-music/|date=21 August 2014|website=Bakermoon.com|publisher=Bakermoon|accessdate=21 August 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906203810/http://www.bakermoon.com/2014/08/recording-in-abbey-road-for-johann-johannsson-theory-of-everything-feature-film-music/|archivedate=6 September 2014|df=dmy-all</ref>

